<HL>
   Canadian Banks
   Lower Prime Rate
   One-Half Point
   ----
   By Rose Tamburri
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
CANADIAN ECONOMIC AND MONETARY NEWS AND ANALYSIS (CEA)
</IN>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- Key Canadian interest rates fell yesterday to
their lowest levels in almost two years amid warnings of a
deepening Canadian economic recession.
   Major commercial banks cut their prime lending rates
one-half percentage point to 12.75%, the lowest level since
February 1989. The prime rate is a benchmark for various
lending rates.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Canadian Manufacturers' Association, an industry
group, said Canada's manufacturing sector "will likely remain
in a recession until at least the third quarter of 1991."
   Royal Bank of Canada economist Michael Gregory, warned
that the current economic recession "is going to get worse."
Canada's gross domestic product declined 0.3% in the second
and third quarters.
   Aron Gampel, senior economist at Bank of Nova Scotia, said
a cut in U.S. short-term rates this week gave the Bank of
Canada room to lower Canadian rates without weakening the
value of the Canadian dollar. The Canadian currency has been
buoyed by wide spreads between comparable Canadian and U.S.
short-term interest rates.
   Despite yesterday's decline, Canadian short-term interest
rates remain more than 4.5 percentage points above U.S.
rates. "That's still a very tough monetary policy," Mr.
Gampel said.
   The Canadian central bank has maintained a restrictive
economic policy because of inflation concerns.
   Some provincial politicians who met with Canadian Finance
Minister Michael Wilson yesterday warned that failure to cut
interest rates further will prolong the current recession. "I
think interest rates have to come down even further," said
Alberta Treasurer Dick Johnston.
   Mr. Wilson said there are still some lingering inflation
pressures in the Canadian economy, particularly high wage
gains. Interest rates are moving lower, Mr. Wilson said. "How
quickly we can achieve that depends on the inflationary
pressures."
   The Canadian Chamber of Commerce urged the government to
freeze spending over the next two years. The group said a
spending freeze was the "only viable solution" for achieving
"lasting reductions" in interest rates.
   Yesterday's prime rate cut followed a drop in the Bank of
Canada's influential bank rate, which fell to 11.78%
yesterday from 12.01%. The bank rate is the levy charged by
the central bank on loans to financial institutions.
   Royal Bank's Mr. Gregory said Canada's short-term interest
rates will likely continue declining until February and then
level off to offset the inflationary impact of Canada's new
7% value-added tax. The new tax, which received final
approval this week, is expected to boost the consumer price
index by a one-time increase of 1.25%. The tax will take
effect Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901221-0159
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901221-0159.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Homeownership Rate Fell
   During the 1980s, to 63.9%
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The rate of homeownership in the U.S. fell
during the 1980s, the first decade-long decline since the
1930s, the government reported.
   The Census Bureau said 63.9% of all households owned their
homes in 1989, down from 65.6% in 1980. Nearly all the rest
rented. Homeownership, however, is still much more common
than it was in 1950, when 55% of households owned their
homes.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The decline in homeownership during the 1980s was
particularly noticeable among younger Americans, who saw
housing prices in some regions soar beyond reach.
   Some 39.1% of households headed by a person under 35 years
old owned homes in 1989, down from 41.2% in 1982, the first
year for which such data are available. Among households
headed by someone over 50, the figure remained constant at
77.2%.
   Although homeownership rates in the Northeast and West
continue to be consistently lower than the national average,
the Northeast was the only region where a higher fraction of
households owned houses at the end of the decade than at the
beginning.
   Patterns of homeownership vary widely; renting is more
common in urban areas. In the District of Columbia, for
instance, only 38.7% of the households own their own homes.
In New York state, the fraction is 52.3% and in California,
it's 53.6%. But in West Virginia, 74.8% of the households own
their homes; in Maine, 73.6% do.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901221-0158
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901221-0158.
</DOCID>
