<HL>
   Real Estate Developer, Aide
   Charged With Loan Fraud
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
BANKS (BNK)
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   BOSTON -- A condominium developer and real estate salesman
were arrested yesterday and charged by federal prosecutors
with bank fraud involving more than $11 million of
condominium loans.
   The 31-count indictment charged that William W. Lilly, 45
years old, a Lynnfield, Mass., developer, and one of his
sales managers, Donald Glusgol, 62, of Peabody, Mass.,
offered falsified condominium mortgages as collateral for
obtaining $7 million in loans from First Mutual Bank for
Savings, a troubled Boston savings bank.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   First Mutual eventually sold the loans for $9 million to
Royal Palm Savings Association, a West Palm Beach, Fla.,
savings and loan that became insolvent and was placed in
conservatorship in April 1989.
   Messrs. Lilly and Glusgol couldn't be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
