<HL>
   Republic Health Says
   First-Quarter Profit
   Totaled $1.1 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   REPH
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Republic Health Corp. expects to report net
income of $1.1 million, or 19 cents a share, for the fiscal
first quarter ended Nov. 30, said Bryan P. Marsal, the
company's chief executive officer.
   In the year-earlier period, then privately held Republic
Health posted a loss of $38 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company expects to report that revenue increased 22%
to $118 million from $97 million, Mr. Marsal said.
   The company had expected its first-quarter earnings to be
"a little higher," Mr. Marsal said in an interview. But he
said the recent 2% reduction in Medicare reimbursements for
outpatient procedures resulted in narrower margins. Republic
Health owns or leases, and operates 13 acute-care hospitals
in six states, plus one surgery center.
   Looking ahead, Mr. Marsal said he expected the company to
stay profitable and to continue posting gains over last
year's results. But he said smaller-than-expected Medicare
reimbursements would continue putting a strain on earnings.
As a result, he said the company is attempting to cut costs,
as well as increase business from non-Medicare patients.
Medicare patients now account for 50% of the company's
business, Mr. Marsal said.
   The company is planning to open two more surgery centers
in Southern California, where its existing one operates, Mr.
Marsal said.
   The chief executive said he expected his company would
prove to be "recession insensitive." But he did say that in
hard times, patients may choose to do without elective
surgery.
   A year ago this month, Republic Health sought Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection to restructure total debt of about $645
million. When it emerged from bankruptcy court in May, its
total debt was reduced to $379 million, and bondholders owned
nearly 90% of its common; the rest was held by holders of the
old preferred and common stock.
   Now, the company has debt of about $350 million and equity
of about $42 million, Mr. Marsal said. He said the company
has no plans to pay dividends or issue additional stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
