<HL>
   Sir Run Run Calls
   Plan for Macy Stake
   Only an Investment
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7C
</SO>
<CO>
   MZ
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
</IN>
<LP>
   HONG KONG -- Sir Run Run Shaw views his plan to buy a
stake in the R.H. Macy &amp; Co. as only an investment, and he
doesn't intend to participate in running the closely held New
York retailer, a spokesman for the movie investor said.
   He is mulling, however, "other forms of participation,"
such as board representation, said the spokesman.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The spokesman acknowledged Macy's problems, including
relatively heavy debt, but he said Sir Run Run regards these
as short-term difficulties. "The company is well-managed.
It's got fine franchises," he said. "We're confident in its
longer-term prospects."
   Macy said this week that it had attracted as much as
US$187.6 million in new equity capital to be used to buy back
some of its depressed high-yield junk bonds. Sir Run Run has
agreed to buy $25 million of Macy's Series III preferred
stock, with an option to invest $25 million more by March 31.
He would become Macy's fourth-largest shareholder if the
option is executed.
   Macy also said that its nonmanagement investors have
agreed to purchase $119 million of Series III preferred stock
and that it has sold $18.6 million of Series II preferred
stock to several shopping-center developers.
   Sir Run Run, 83 years old, is among Hong Kong's wealthiest
individuals. His fortune is founded on the entertainment
business, but he also invests heavily in real estate. Macy is
his first major investment in the retail business.
   The Macy stake, like much of his wealth, is held
privately. His principal listed vehicle, Shaw Brothers (Hong
Kong) Ltd., owns movie theaters, produces movies and licenses
film releases. His about 67% stake in the company, at current
market prices, is valued at about HK$1 billion, or US$128.2
million).
   Through Shaw Brothers, Sir Run Run also controls
Television Broadcasts Ltd., which dominates Hong Kong's
television-broadcasting industry.
   The spokesman says Sir Run Run has no plans to boost his
Macy stake beyond what has been provided for in the option.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901221-0123
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901221-0123.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Movies:
   Disney's Star Is Foreign to U.S. Audiences
   ----
   By Richard Turner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   DIS
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   HOLLYWOOD -- What Pele was to soccer, Gerard Depardieu is
to movies. In much of the world, particularly in Western
Europe, he is acclaimed as the greatest living screen actor,
a French Brando, a legend.
   But in the U.S., people ask "Who?"
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Moreover, as Walt Disney Co. film executives found when
testing brief TV ads with audiences, many Americans' initial
impression of the shaggy, beefy, big-nosed actor was that he
was a "fat slob."
   The female lead in the coming film "Green Card" has the
same reaction, but after a while she falls madly in love.
Disney's vaunted marketing machine must ensure that audiences
do the same.
   But first, they have to get people to show up. The main
thing people ask when they hear that a film is a love story
is "Who's in it?" But the movie's co-star, Andie MacDowell of
"sex, lies, and videotape," is also relatively unknown.
   The subject matter of this small-scale romantic comedy
won't help sell it either, even if the idea is easy to sum up
on a poster: "The story of two people who got married, met,
and then fell in love." Hollywood generally loves concepts
that can be explained in a sentence: Two strangers, a scruffy
Frenchman and a slightly priggish American horticulturist,
get married, he to gain residency status, she to get an
apartment she covets. But however packageable the idea seems,
it doesn't hold any special allure.
   "It's outside most people's experience," concedes Peter
Weir, who wrote, produced and directed "Green Card."
   The marketing difficulties are especially frustrating
because Disney executives are proud of the film. Disney
Studios Chairman Jeffrey Katzenberg has taken it as a
personal challenge to successfully open the movie, which some
Disney wags are calling "`Pretty Woman' for people who
think." The poster for "Green Card" bears more than a passing
resemblance to the one used for "Pretty Woman," Disney's
biggest hit ever.
   Christmas is a crowded, competitive time, especially for
fragile movies, but "Green Card" is being released Sunday to
qualify it for Academy Award consideration. Most reviews
aren't out yet, but they're likely to be generally favorable.
Rolling Stone called it "captivating" but with "all the heft
of a potato chip." Mr. Weir, the Australian director who made
"The Year of Living Dangerously" and "Witness," is highly
regarded. Disney gets prestige points no matter what, but a
success would help redeem a winter season when Disney's
"Three Men and a Little Lady" and "Rescuers Down Under" were
snowed under by Fox's "Home Alone."
   It would surpass Disney executives' wildest dreams if the
film won the kind of audience attracted by other urban fare
like "Moonstruck" and "When Harry Met Sally." But the
marketing of the film is a slow and arduous process; it's
definitely not just a matter of buying the right TV time. Mr.
Katzenberg has criss-crossed the country to be the host at
upscale screenings followed by receptions at New York's 21
Club, Hollywood's Morton's and the Los Angeles County Museum
of Art.
   This is an effort to reach "opinionmakers," says Disney
marketing chief Robert Levin. Through word-of-mouth, he hopes
the film will do well in New York and Los Angeles, then build
gradually as it goes to a still-selective 100 screens Jan 11.
If any kind of buzz continues and if other Christmas movies
wither, Disney hopes theater owners will make room for "Green
Card" on more and more screens.
   Disney is walking a tightrope. It needs Mr. Depardieu's
tiny art-house following to help launch the picture, but if
the film is perceived as too arty, it could turn off wider
segments of the audience.
   "When someone is confronted with a piece of material, they
can say, `I get it, but I think you have to be smart,'" says
Mr. Levin. "They're afraid that they're going to wind up in
the audience and not get the joke when everyone else does."
   So the TV spots and theatrical trailer rather mundanely
explain the idea and show a little romance and comedy. Mr.
Levin says the only reason the trailer even mentions that Mr.
Depardieu is "the most acclaimed actor in France" is so the
handful of people who know this will be reassured that Disney
is aware of it. "The rest of the people will say, `Big
deal.'"
   Disney hasn't been too proud to try some Hollywood
gimmicks, but they, too, have been problematic. The marketing
people placed classified ads seeking couples who got married
so one partner could get a green card to stay in the U.S.,
thinking they would be fodder for talk shows that would also
mention the film. "But it appears only to have generated the
interest of the INS," says Mr. Levin. As in the film, the
Immigration and Naturalization Service doesn't care if the
couple are in love and want to live happily ever after; the
initial act is still fraud.
   Mr. Weir thought up the movie's premise three years ago
after returning to Australia to take a year off, licking his
wounds from the disappointing opening of "The Mosquito
Coast." He wound up writing the script with Mr. Depardieu in
mind, even though he had never met him and didn't know
whether Mr. Depardieu could speak English. (He can, sort of.)
   Disney has an aggressively hands-on attitude about its
films and generally steers clear of renowned directors for
this reason, but Mr. Weir and Mr. Katzenberg, who did "Dead
Poets Society" together, get along well. Although Mr. Weir
says Disney shows "excessive zeal" about enforcing budgetary
constraints and can be "bureaucratic," he was left alone on
"Green Card" because the $12 million film was independently
produced. Mr. Depardieu and Mr. Weir accepted reduced fees to
meet the budget, nothing new for the French actor who once
starred in a movie for a struggling director in return for a
bottle of wine. (He did stipulate that it be a very good
bottle.)
   Disney executives seemed resigned to allowing Mr. Weir to
make the film his way. They couldn't get him to cast a bigger
name than Ms. MacDowell or to broaden the comedy elements.
They didn't push too hard about Mr. Weir's refusal to give
the film a "Pretty Woman" fairy-tale ending. They would just
say, "Don't you realize that if you recut this, you could buy
a new house?" Mr. Weir recalls.
   But now Mr. Weir needs Disney to get people into theaters,
and the director sees some irony in this. The movie industry,
he says, "has trained audiences to respond to a siren song:
`Come and get it, you'll like it,' and it's turned into a
Frankenstein monster. They release all these dumb movies, and
then when they have one they like -- one everybody likes,
that's simple and honest -- it turns out to be difficult to
sell."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901221-0122
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901221-0122.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Mutual Funds:
   Does Wave of Muni Mania
   Mean Now Is Time to Sell?
   ----
   By Jonathan Clements
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Mutual fund investors, shrugging off the
recent spate of bad news about state and city budgets, are
throwing money at municipal bond funds at a feverish pace.
   Investors are eager to minimize taxes and they "sense that
this is the last game in town," says Dale Rabiner, manager of
the $160 million Bartlett Fixed Income Fund, a no-load mutual
fund based in Cincinnati.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mutual fund investors are notoriously bad at guessing
market swings. So the municipal-bond buying binge is
prompting some nervousness. "Time and time again, contrarian
thinking pays off," Mr. Rabiner notes.
   Single-state municipal bond funds were the best-selling
category of mutual funds in 1989. And they are on track for
another chart-topping year.
   According to the Investment Company Institute, the trade
group for the mutual fund industry, $5.3 billion flooded into
single-state funds in the first 10 months of this year. That
inflow outstripped any other mutual fund category except
money market funds. General municipal bond funds also did
well, pulling in $3.2 billion. These figures represent sales
minus redemptions, plus the net effect of switches involving
other funds in the same family; reinvested dividends are
excluded.
   Some fund managers believe the current muni mania is
entirely justified. "The municipals haven't rallied as much
as Treasurys," Ian MacKinnon, Vanguard Group's head of fixed
income, says. "Clearly, munis are at the cheap end of their
trading range, compared to Treasurys. We think it's a smart
idea to buy munis right now."
   But if fund investors' current enthusiasm for municipal
bonds does foretell a coming decline, it wouldn't be the
first time.
   Fund investors bought stock funds heavily prior to both
the 1987 and 1990 bear markets. They also poured money into
U.S. government and tax-free bond funds right up until the
April 1987 bond market slump. In 1988, high-yield "junk" bond
funds pulled in more money than any other mutual fund
category. The following year, the junk bond market started
unraveling.
   Why are fund investors such poor market-timers? Mr.
Rabiner says that when it comes to bonds, the problem arises
because many fund investors buy based on yield. What they
should really look at, he says, is total return, which
includes both the share-price change and the yield. This is
because prices for older bonds will slump whenever yields are
rising.
   Lately, few investments have matched the yield offered by
municipal bond funds. According to Lipper Analytical
Services, general municipal bond funds have yielded 6.7% over
the past 12 months. Figure in a top 33% tax rate, and this
yield is worth 10% on a pretax basis. Among the major fund
categories tracked by Lipper, only two groups have offered a
higher yield, junk bond funds and short-term world income
funds.
   So far, municipal bond investors have done pretty well.
Over the past 12 months, there hasn't been too much disparity
between the yields on municipal funds and the total return.
   "Compared to stocks, owning municipals has been
brilliant," Guy Wickwire, manager of Fidelity High Yield
Tax-Free Portfolio, says. "There have been isolated, small
defaults over the last few years, and if the economy
continues to be bad, we will probably have more. But I don't
think the defaults will pick up any."
   Bartlett's Mr. Rabiner, however, reckons problems may lie
ahead. He notes that many state and local governments are
struggling with budget deficits, and yet the yield spread
between the highest-rated and lowest-rated municipal bonds is
still relatively narrow.
   Mr. Rabiner says investors should make sure it really
makes sense for them to be in a municipal bond fund, given
their income levels. He suggests fund investors might want to
switch out of high-yield municipal bond funds and
state-specific funds and into a high-quality general
municipal bond fund. Even people in high-quality funds should
be prepared to sit tight in the face of short-term losses
caused as credit problems hurt the price of all municipal
bonds, he believes.
   But others see little reason to worry. "I think it's a
myth that fund investors are generally wrong," Avi Nachmany,
a fund analyst with Jesup, Josephthal &amp; Co., says. He points
out that the recent returns of municipal bonds haven't been
lavish enough to prompt speculative buying. Mr. Nachmany
reckons that investors have been buying municipal bond funds
simply to shelter income.
   ---
   For First Investors Consolidated Corp., the bad news keeps
on coming.
   The New York-based mutual fund company, which is already
battling charges of sales abuse brought against it by New
York and Massachusetts, has just lost its top fund manager.
Daniel Duane, who used to run the top-performing First
Investors Global Fund, has left to run three funds managed by
Prudential Equity Management Associates, a subsidiary of
Prudential Insurance Co. of America, Newark, N.J.
   "We don't like to lose anybody," says David Grayson, First
Investors president. "But we do have his {Mr. Duane's}
righthand person, who worked with him, taking over the fund."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
