<HL>
   ConAgra Earnings,
   Sales Increased 38%
   In Second Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CAG X.BCI
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<LP>
   OMAHA, Neb. -- ConAgra Inc., its results swollen by its
recent $1.34 billion acquisition of Beatrice Co., reported a
38% jump in both earnings and sales for the second quarter
ended Nov. 25.
   The food concern said net income rose to $88.3 million, or
60 cents a share, from the year-earlier $63.9 million, or 52
cents a share. Sales climbed to $5.33 billion from $3.86
billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Per-share earnings reflect an increase in the number of
common and equivalent shares to 137 million from the year-ago
122.7 million. ConAgra, as part of the Beatrice acquisition,
issued seller Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. more than 11
million common shares, along with 142,000 shares of
convertible preferred.
   In addition, per-share figures in the latest period also
reflect the payment of $6.1 million in preferred dividends:
such payments are deducted before per-share earnings are
calculated. In the year-ago quarter, ConAgra had only a
nominal $147,000 in preferred payments.
   The company said its latest earnings were "highlighted by
good earnings balance, aggressive activity in new consumer
products and excellent progress bringing the Beatrice
businesses on board."
   Beatrice earnings, only two weeks of which were included
in the fiscal first quarter results, "to date have been ahead
of plan," ConAgra said.
</TEXT>
