<HL>
   U.S. Reserve Assets
   In November Rose
   To $83.06 Billion
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
U.S. ECONOMIC INDICATORS (EMI)
FORECASTS AND ANALYSIS OF U.S. ECONOMIC INDICATORS (EMJ)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- U.S. reserve assets rose $207 million in
November to $83.06 billion.
   The latest figure compares with the $72.57 billion level
of reserve assets in November 1989, the Treasury said. Last
month's rise followed a $2.83 billion rise in October.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   U.S. reserve assets consist of foreign currencies, gold,
special drawing rights at the International Monetary Fund and
the U.S. reserve position at the IMF.
   The Treasury report showed U.S. holdings of foreign
currencies rose $220 million in November to $52.07 billion.
That's up $9.37 billion from November 1989.
   The U.S. gold stock was down $1 million in November to
$11.06 billion from the prior month. A year earlier, it was
at about the same level.
   The country's ability to draw foreign currency from the
International Monetary Fund decreased $195 million in
November to $8.87 billion. That is down from $9.06 billion a
year earlier.
   U.S. holdings of IMF special drawing rights were up $183
million last month to $11.06 billion. That compares with
$9.75 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
