<HL>
   Business Brief -- Shaw Brothers (Hong Kong) Ltd.:
   Firm's Net Income Fell 27%
   For Half From Write-Down
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7C
</SO>
<CO>
   H.SHB
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Shaw Brothers (Hong Kong) Ltd. said net income for the six
months ended Sept. 30 tumbled 27% to 54 million Hong Kong
dollars (US$6.9 million) from HK$74 million a year earlier.
   For the period, the film and property group controlled by
Sir Run Run Shaw had a write-down of HK$34 million on its
investment in Hong Kong Cable Communications Ltd., the local
cable-TV franchise that was abandoned last month by its five
partners.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Excluding the write-down, the company said profit climbed
19% to HK$88 million. Earnings per share dropped to 13.62
Hong Kong cents a share from 18.46 Hong Kong cents a share,
while revenue grew 8.7% to HK$100 million from HK$92 million.
   Group directors proposed an interim dividend of seven
cents a share, unchanged from a year earlier.
   Shaw Brothers attributed the growth in operating profit to
an increased contribution from its Singapore property arm,
following the renovation of a commercial building it owns
there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
