<HL>
   Business Brief -- Yerkes &amp; Michels:
   Accounting Firm Is Banned
   From Serving Any Thrifts
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
ACCOUNTING (ACC)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   The Office of Thrift Supervision permanently banned Yerkes
&amp; Michels, an accounting firm based in Independence, Kan.,
from serving any thrift, thrift-holding company or subsidiary
that is federally regulated.
   Under a consent order in connection with the firm's audit
of First Federal Savings &amp; Loan Association of Independence,
the thrift office charged that the 1988 and 1989 audits
weren't conducted by qualified public accountants. The thrift
office also said that Yerkes &amp; Michels reported the true
financial condition of First Federal, which meets all capital
requirements, but that it relied on government examiners'
paperwork, and didn't independently review the thrift.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Yerkes &amp; Michels couldn't be reached for comment. Under
the consent order, the firm neither admits nor denies the
grounds of the order.
   The thrift office also issued a cease-and-desist order
requiring Yerkes &amp; Michels to correct its auditing practices,
and repay audit fees of $51,000 that the firm charged First
Federal. It must also establish minimum credentials for any
partners and staff assigned to bank or credit union audits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901221-0015
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901221-0015.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Black &amp; Decker Corp.:
   Emerson Electric to Buy
   Mallory Unit for $90 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
12/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   BDK EMR
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Black &amp; Decker Corp. said it agreed to sell its North
American Mallory Controls business for $90 million but
expects to report fourth-quarter earnings lower than
previously estimated.
   The Towson, Md., power-tool maker said it sold Mallory
Controls, which it acquired as part of last year's
acquisition of Emhart Corp., to Emerson Electric Co. It said
the Brazilian portion of the business is being offered for
sale separately.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Emerson Electric, a St. Louis-based maker of electronic
products, couldn't be reached for comment.
   Black &amp; Decker has been selling assets in order to meet
payments on the $2.8 billion loan it used to buy Emhart. Last
month it sold its U.S. and Canadian assets in True Temper
Hardware as well as capital stock in True Temper Ltd. in
Ireland to Huffy Corp. for $55 million.
   The company also said it expects lower earnings due to
lower sales in the U.S. and deteriorating business conditions
in Brazil. "While we expect to offset most of the
sluggishness in the U.S. through aggressive cost-containment
programs, the difficulties in Brazil will result in
lower-than-expected earnings in the fourth quarter," said
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Nolan D. Archibald.
However, he also noted that the company expects a profitable
fourth quarter compared with the net loss it reported last
year.
   Mr. Archibald said the company is actively pursuing the
sale of the Brazilian Mallory Controls business and will
implement major cost reductions in all Brazil operations.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Black
&amp; Decker shares closed down 25 cents to $10.75.
</TEXT>
